The '''Sibiu Literary Circle''' ({{lang-ro|Cercul literar de la Sibiu}}) was a [[literary society|literary group]] created during [[World War II]] in [[Sibiu]] to promote the modernist liberal ideas of [[Eugen Lovinescu]].
The group was formed around [[Lucian Blaga]] and other intellectuals from [[Cluj-Napoca|Cluj]], who had settled in Sibiu after the [[Babeş-Bolyai University|University of Cluj]] had moved there in 1940, in the wake of the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] occupation of [[Northern Transylvania]]. The most active members of the group were [[Ion Negoițescu]], [[Radu Stanca]], [[Ion Desideriu Sârbu]], [[Cornel Regman]], [[Ștefan Augustin Doinaș]], [[Nicolae Balotă]], [[Eugen Todoran]], [[Eta Boeriu]], [[Radu Enescu]], and [[Ovidiu Cotruş]]. The group disbanded in 1945.
==References== * Ovidiu S. Crohmălniceanu, ''Cercul literar de la Sibiu şi influenţa catalitică a culturii germane'', [[Bucharest]]: Editura Universalia, 2000. {{ISBN|973-99274-0-8}} * Petru Poantă, ''Cercul literar de la Sibiu. Introducere în fenomenul originar'', Cluj-Napoca: Clusium, 1997. {{ISBN|973-555-163-2}}
